The Top Twitch Streamers Analysis Tutorial¶

by Aaron Oh, Kevin Chong, Haider Sajid, Rohith Chandu

Introduction¶

This Data Science Tutorial is brought to you by the 4 man team from the University of Maryland. We will be doing an analysis on a data set from the top 1000 Twitch streamers from around the world. The Twitch data set includes different types of data on streamers such as the number of followers, number of average viewers, watch time, and other relevant types of data about a Twitch streamer which we will be analyzing to determine how and what makes a Twitch streamer successful.

Motivation¶

So why is this important in Data Science? Not only will it be beneficial for Twitch streamers, but it will also benefit others who are interested on how and why streaming on Twitch is so popular. By data scraping, we can figure out numerous things such as whether or not mature rated content is more advantageous when trying to gain followers. We can also dissect whether followers gained affects stream time or vice versa. All these things can contribute to learning more about the Twitch streaming community. It can help new creators discover the best/and fastest way to become popular on this streaming platform as well as give insight on why Twitch streaming is such a popular platform among this generation.

Background Information¶

Twitch is an American video live streaming service that officially launched in 2011. The streaming service focuses on video game live streaming. Not only do they broadcast epsorts competions, but they also offer creative content and music broadcasts as well as "in real life" streams. The platform also creates a learning environment and is often used for video game tutorials. The streaming service is not only limited to learning about video games, but can also be used for learning software development, with streamers broadcasting progamming projects and discussing their work with the community. Twitch had more than 100 million viewers per month by 2015. In 2017, Twitch also remained the leader of live streaming video services for video games in the USA as well as having an advantage over the popular YouTube gaming. As of February 2020, the streaming service had 3 million broadcasters monthly, but also 15 million daily active users, with on average 1.4 million concurrent users. Twitch had over 27,000 partner channels as of May 2018.

Data Scraping¶

Before we begin we will be sourcing our data from this website. This website contains the CSV (comma-separated values) file on the top 1000 Twitch streamers. The dataset also includes 11 columns of different types of data on Twitch streamers.

Set Up

First we will import the necessary packages being used in our tutorial. These packages will essentially allow us to utilize different types of functions in order to represent our data visually using different kinds of graphs. Also, we are able to upload our downloaded csv file through here.

Data Vizualization and Analysis¶

By creating a line plot of the top 20 streamers and their respective stream times, we can determine whether or not streaming time contributes to popularity of a streamer. We see here that we also used a seaborn plot in order to create a line graph to view the correlation between stream time and watch time. If you would like to learn more about seaborn and its plotting function visit the link here.

In [193]:
topfive = df.head(20)
channels = topfive['Channel']
stream = topfive['Stream time(minutes)']
plt.subplots(figsize = (30,8))
sns.lineplot(x=channels, y=stream, data=topfive)
plt.title("Top 20 Channels(Watch Time Based) & Stream Time(Minutes)")
plt.xlabel("Channel")
plt.ylabel("Stream Time(Minutes)")

Based on the line plot, we can observe that the top 5 streamers do stream more minutes compared to the latter. This means that stream time does play a role when it comes to popularity. Quantity seems to be an important factor when it comes to Twitch streaming. In addition, this line plot allows us, as analysts, to easily identify which streamer is the most popular. As we can see, the streamer "xQc0W" had approximately 20,000 minutes in stream time, which is slightly above the next streamer in the line plot, summit1g. Following summit1g, there is a huge exponential growth in stream time as we approach the next streamers, Gaules and ESL_CSGO. Gaules and ESL_CSGO have approximately 50,0000 minutes in stream time which is the highest in our dataset.

Approach¶

After a closer look at our data set, we observed that the top 5 streamers in general stream for longer periods of time. This brought up the question of whether or not the top streamers get their views and followers during the stream or after the stream (Twitch Recaps). We wanted to determine if there was a relationship between watch/stream time, viewers, and followers. We also wanted to see if mature content was more advantageous when it comes to watch time/popularity in comparison to the opposite. Since each streamer had their unique data set, graphs such as violin plots would not be helpful. However, bar graphs, line graphs, pie charts, and other plots that showed differences in our data (specifically the trend of different streamers) were paramount. We first wanted to see the correlation between the twitch categories in the data set.

In [194]:
plt.figure(figsize=(9,6))
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap='Purples')
plt.show()

Here we have a heat map. This is another great visiual data representation given to us by the seaborn package. The heat map is able to tell us how strong the correlation between two data categories are using color shade. The darker the shade of purple means that they will have a stronger correlation while lighter shades have a weaker correlation. In this heat map we can see that other than the fully purple blocks along the diagonal, the second highest value is 0.72 between followers and followers gained. From this map, we can also observe that there are rather high correlations between followers and watch time, peak viewers and average viewers, and followers and followers gained.

By creating a bar plot with the top 20 twitch streamers and their average viewers per stream, we can determine if the best streamers get their views/popularity after or during a stream.

Above, we created a scatter plot which plots data in respect to average viewers and their stream time. Although the data points aren't labeled with the names of the streamers, this scatter plot still provides us with plenty of information to analyze. The streamer with the least amount of viewers gets approximately 8000 viewers whereas the streamer with the most viewers gets over 50,000.

Based on the above pie chart which displays the top 10 channels based on peak viewers, we are able to see that the top 5 channels in terms of peak viewers are Tfue, ESL_CSGO, Gaules, summit1g, and Asmongold. We can see based on the prior pie graphs of "Total Followers" and "Average viewers" that there is not that strong of a correlation between a streamer's peak viewers vs their total viewers or average. Just because a streamer recieved the most views on a particular video doesn't necessarily conclude that the streamer has the most amount of average consistent viewers on a basis. For example, according to the pie graph above, Gaules has the highest peak viewers, consisting of 17.8% of the pie graph, however, when we analyze the pie graph for Total Followers and Average viewers, we are able to see that Gaules is not even listed on those two other pie graphs.

Based on the two bar graphs shown above displaying the top 10 channels based on Views gained and followers gained, we can confirm that there is some sort of correlation between the two. Out of the 1,000 channels being displayed in the entire data set, when narrowing it down to the top 10 in both these categories we can see that channel 600 (Tfue) and channel 893 (xQcOW) appear in the top 10 for both views gained and followers gained. Since we are only observing a small subset and 2 out of the 10 appear in both of these graphs, we can confirm that followers gained within a channel tends to lead to an increase in views. This ultimately makes sense since when channels attract more followers, they have more people that are notified of their streams when they are going live. On twitch these notifications to followers plays a huge role in the amount of viewers the stream receives.

Conclusion¶

In this tutorial, we wanted to analyze the dataset of the top 1000 Twitch streamers around the world. Analyzing the information we got from the dataset along with visual representations of it allowed us to dive deeper into the correlation between Twitch data categories. From this, we discovered that the top streamers generally stream for longer periods of time as opposed to those who have a lesser following. We also found that mature content gets more followers and views. In addition to that, we discovered the most popular streamers are getting their views and popularity after their streams have ended on Twitch Recap due to other streamers having a higher average live view count.

The data that we analyzed helped us have a better understanding about what really makes a twitch streamer be in the top percentile. Based on the analysis of each subcategory, some streamers had a lot more peak viewers than they did average viewers, some streamers had a lot more average view time than they did averager viewers, and some had a lot more followers than other. All of this information helped us determine that to be a top streamer, there are a variety of different factors that come into play.
